Key Patterns
Walmart and Verizon are routing hubs. Both can transfer to nearly every other active workflow. Walmart has 9 outbound transfer targets; Verizon has 9 as well. Walmart additionally acts as a document classification hub where scanned documents are sorted and routed to the correct downstream workflow.

ESC is both an escalation catch-all and the most connected workflow. Every major workflow can transfer TO ESC. ESC also has 12+ outbound transfer targets (including a self-transfer for re-routing within ESC), making it the most connected domain. CRM (Complaint/Regulatory Management) is a sub-type within ESC that receives transfers labeled "TransferToCRM."

Lockbox sub-targets (NJEA, MLBO, COSC) are reached via named transfer classes rather than a generic "TransferToLockbox." Each maps to a specific business unit within the Lockbox workflow.

LCMS sub-workflows transfer internally. Documents entering LCMS auto-assign are routed to GLCD, PEB, OSGLI, or ILI sub-workflows based on form code. TransferHelperLCMS manages this routing.

Records management triggers on transfer. When items are transferred OUT of GUL/GVUL (workflow 9) or OSGLI (workflow 3), the system sets a records-management destruction date via GulGvulRecordsAdminHelper or OSGLIRecordsAdminHelper.

